2. Use the traceroute (tracert on Windows, traceroute on Linux/Mac) command to trace the path from your computer to www.flipkart.com. List the number of hops and identify the IP address of the first and last hop.
=>Command used (Windows): tracert www.flipkart.com
Number of hops: Usually 8–15 hops depending on your ISP and location.
First hop: Local router/gateway (e.g., 192.168.1.1 or your ISP's first router).
Last hop: One of Flipkart’s CDN or server IPs
3. Simulate a connectivity issue by pinging a non-existent website (for example, ping www.fakezomato12345.com) and write down the error message you receive.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> Compare the output to a successful ping and describe the difference in your findings.</em>
=>Ping request could not find host www.fakezomato12345.com. Please check the name and try again.
Comparison with Successful Ping:
Successful ping (e.g., Spotify): Resolves domain name → shows IP address → sends/receives ICMP packets with low latency.
Failed ping (fake domain): Fails at DNS resolution stage. No IP address is returned, so no packets are sent. This indicates a DNS lookup failure rather than a routing or connectivity problem.

4. Imagine you are unable to access www.youtube.com from your system. Use both ping and traceroute commands to diagnose the issue and write a short report describing where the connection fails and what the possible reasons could be
=>ping www.youtube.com
tracert www.youtube.com   
DNS Issue — Local DNS cache corrupted (solution: ipconfig /flushdns).
ISP Routing Problem — Temporary outage or peering issue with Google’s network.
Firewall / Proxy — Corporate or security software blocking YouTube traffic.
MTU Fragmentation — Packet size issues causing blackholing.
YouTube-side — Rare regional outage
